In addition to confirming that at least some dinosaurs were feathered, the theory also offers specific data that fossils generally do not offer, such as their color and their three-dimensional structure.
According to the experts, this animal has a brown plumage on the upper part and a pale or carotinoid tonality on the lower part.
In addition, the discovery allows us to better understand the evolution of the feathers of birds.
Given that the plumage of dinosaurs does not have a well-developed rachis, but rather presents other features of feathers (bristles and barbs), the researchers came to the conclusion that it is likely that the rachis is the result of a subsequent evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure that presents the plumage suggests that its function was not related to the flight, but that they were used to regulate the temperature or as an indicator of the same. The researchers maintain that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample analyzed presents features of the plumage of an adult and not of a chick.
The opinions of the experts were that, even though it is the tail of a short-lived dinosaur, the specimen illustrates more the plumage of an adult than that of a juvenile.
